review: Nomadland: Surviving America in the Twenty-First Century by Jessica Bruder is a critically acclaimed work of travel nonfiction and literary reportage Nomadland: Surviving America in the Twenty-First Century by Jessica Bruder is a critically acclaimed work of travel nonfiction and literary reportage that was first published in 2017. The book pieces together the stories of several people Bruder follows over three years. It incorporates historical and social context for their decision to live out of vans or mobile homes. It was made into an academy award winning movie in 2020. Three of the people we meet in the book also were featured in the movie. Awesome book and awesome movie. I read one and watched the other. From the book:"After the New Deal, economists began referring to America’s retirement-finance model as a “three-legged stool.” This sturdy tripod was composed of Social Security, private pensions, and combined investments and savings. In recent years, of course, two of those legs have been kicked out."To a man/woman, this phenomenon has struck the people described in this book. Some lost their homes because of company shutdowns; others lost retirement savings because of the 2008 Market Crash. Many people in their position would have lived with family if possible. But the folks described here yearned for independence and struck out on their own.This book is painstakingly researched and describes the culture of the nomad. Many travel from seasonal job to seasonal job. Three of the ones mentioned are US Forestry Camp Hosts, work in many of the Amazon warehouses through the WorkKamper program and (!) dealing in poker tournaments.I never knew this segment of society existed. I wavered between awe of their lifestyle and guilt because I do not suffer their particularly difficult life.Anybody who will listen is told by me: 'READ THIS BOOK; YOUR EYES WILL BE OPENED'. I have also said that this book is the best book I have read THIS CENTURY (!!). It provides so much information and so much to discuss and think about.Ask my BookClub who found much to discuss and agree and disagree (!!) about.5 stars...more

The manuscript, or "Harry Haller’s Records," consists of three sections: events that occur prior to the treatise; "the Treatise on the Steppenwolf"; and events occurring after the treatise, namely meeting Hermine and visiting the Magic Theater.My ImpressionsI found the story quite a study in the human psyche. Harry was continuously fighting between his dual natures: that of wolf and that of man. Because of his dual natures, he must separate himself from society and is very lonely.He does meet and interact with Hermine, Maria and Pablo who help him to enjoy life as never before.There are three main 'events' in this story: meeting Hermine who teaches him to dance, attending the Masked Ball and visiting the Magic Theatre (very strange thins happen there).Glad I read it.4 stars  ...more

review: Dwight Longenecker is a a married Catholic priest. I learned this from his Goodreads biographical paragraph."Dwight Longenecker was brought up an EvanDwight Longenecker is a a married Catholic priest. I learned this from his Goodreads biographical paragraph."Dwight Longenecker was brought up an Evangelical, studied at the fundamentalist Bob Jones University, and later was ordained an Anglican priest in England. After ten years in the Anglican ministry as a curate, a chaplain at Cambridge, and a country parson, in 1995 Dwight was received into full communion with the Catholic Church."The auhtenticity of the magi story has been a topic near and dear to his heart for a few years.From his Author note:"The idea for Mystery of the Magi first appeared when Dr. Matthew Bunson asked me to write an article about the origins of the wise men for Catholic Answers magazine. I was aware of the opinions of the academics that the Magi story was either a fantasy, or that the Magi (if they existed) were Zoroastrian priests from Parthia.I wondered, however, if there might be more than meets the eye, and I asked whether the Old Testament prophecies about the Magi might indicate their origin."Here is what I learned.Father refers to the Magi story as related in the gospel of Matthew. It does not name the Magi; it does not say they rode camels; it merely says they came 'from the East'. Seems that over the years the Magi story was embellished to the point of craziness by many, but especially the Gnostics.So....Father answers the questions:Were there Magi? Father believes there IS historical data to support their existence.Where did they come from? Arabia, not PersiaWhat was the 'star'? A comet or a planet? Was Paul influenced by the Magi of Petra?My favorite chapter is Chapter 12 in which Father takes the simple story of the Magi in Matthew's Gospel and disects it line by line. If you read nothing else in this book, read that. I believe the chapter stands on its own.5 stars...more

It is set in Japan after World War II, and focuses on an orphaned young man named Kikuji. He becomes involved with Mrs. Ota, a former mistress of his father. The book centers on the Japanese Tea Ceremony and begins with a description of this cultural event."THE BEGINNINGS of the tea cult can be traced to the thirteenth century and the beginnings of Zen Buddhism in Japan. Early Zen masters recommended tea as the beverage most excellent for cultivating the spirit, and in the centuries that followed, an elaborate symbolism and a carefully contrived ritual encouraged the Zen disciple in his aim to achieve imperturbability."The characters are many and diverse:Kikuji, the protagonistChikako Kurimoto, a former mistress of Kikuji's fatherMrs. Ota, a former mistress of Kikuji's fatherFumiko, Mrs. Ota's daughterYukiko Inamura, a pupil of Miss KurimotoI very much enjoyed reading this window into Japanese Culture. review: Both listened to and read The Searcher by Tana French.Summary (obtained from supersummary.com):The Searcher (2020) is a novel by Irish American authorBoth listened to and read The Searcher by Tana French.Summary (obtained from supersummary.com):The Searcher (2020) is a novel by Irish American author Tana French, who has made a name for herself penning literary fiction with the plot and pacing of a crime novel. This novel described as Tana French’s Irish Western features a retired policeman and a missing boy.The protagonist, Cal, is an American ex-cop who retires in the West of Ireland and spends ample time refurbishing his home before fate has other plans for him. French’s novel has a “western tinge” in being inspired by the American western trope of an outsider coming into a community and changing everything around them. Forty-eight-year-old Cal Hooper moves to the rural West of Ireland from Chicago to undertake early retirement and leave his past behind. Following his divorce, his estrangement from his daughter Alyssa and his disenchantment with his job as a police officer, Cal decides to seek out an existence of fishing, rabbit hunting and home refurbishment in the rural village of Ardnakelty. The close-knit community of locals treat him as a curiosity and attempt to include him by inviting him to the local pub or, in the case of the convenience store owner Noreen, attempting to set him up with her widowed sister Lena.At first, when Cal realizes that he is being watched, he tries to ignore the matter. However, his spy turns out to be the determined 13-year-old Trey Reddy. Despite Cal’s wish to conceal the knowledge, Trey is aware that Cal was a former cop, and he wants him to help find his brother Brendan, who disappeared six months earlier. He acquiesces and the plot continues as Cal interviews locals to determine Brendan Reddy's fate.The CharactersCal Hooper - 48 year old ex-cop from ChicagoTrey Reddy - 13 year old brother of the missing elder brother, Brendan Reddy Brendan Reddy - the reader does not 'meet' him, but the memory of him looms large in the communitySheila Reddy - their motherMart Lavin - Cal's neighbor who portrays himself as the bumbling busybodyMy ImpressionsSlow paced. We learn a lot about how Cal thinks when he shares his thoughts with us and shares them with Trey. The most impressive of these is Cal's idea of good and evil. He describes himself as 'having a code' and he sees Trey that way too.The voice of Roger Clark as audio narrator adds another dimension to Cal. Clark's voice is unique and assists in the listener/reader's ability to really visualize Cal.I am not usually a crime story reader, but the easy accessibility of the audio book so that I could listen as I drive, convinced me to try this novel. Glad that I did.4 stars...more

review: One of Jodi Picoult's best books.It describes the experiences of Diana O'Toole and her boyfriend Dr. Finn Colson during the Covid-19 pandemic.It surprOne of Jodi Picoult's best books.It describes the experiences of Diana O'Toole and her boyfriend Dr. Finn Colson during the Covid-19 pandemic.It surprised me how quickly I have forgotten how very horrible the pandemic was. The many deaths and the overwhelming effects on hospital employees were well described here. How amazing that these descriptions still 'took me by surprise'.Piccoult wrote this book in two months. She suffers from asthma and was negatively impacted by Covid. She states in her author interview that she wrote this book as therapy:"This pandemic ROCKED me. I have never felt so adrift in my life, or more aware that I am a “lawful good” kind of person—the kind who plans, organizes, and follows rules. Suddenly I had no control over anything, and I was a mess. Since I had no power over my own future in that moment, I wrote the book as a therapeutic way to control something."I am discussing with my book club this Thursday, Dec 1, 2022. I know the discussion will be awesome.Update Dec 2: I am not alone in choosing this book as Picoult's best or close to!! At least two others of the club felt the same way.I do not want to discuss any more particulars here, as I want YOU to read it and see for yourself what a clever and well written book this is.5 stars...more

review: Another very well written book by Amy Bloom.However, the subject matter is painful.The book describes the relationship betwen Eleanor Roosevelt and LoAnother very well written book by Amy Bloom.However, the subject matter is painful.The book describes the relationship betwen Eleanor Roosevelt and Lorena Hickok ("Hick"). Hick is a journalist who interviews FDR during his first presidential campain. She meets Eleanor and they fall in love. FDR is described as knowing about the relationship and allows it to exist. Just as Eleanor knows about FDR's liaisons and looks the other way. The story is narrated by Hick. Hick is a strong character and I loved reading her thoughts, at least at first. She describes the event that helped her to realize she was a lesbian. Poignant account. But she shows a lot of anger and resentment too and this became hard to read. She painted FDR in ugly colors and I did not appreciate this picture. But I LOVE Amy Bloom and have thoroughly enjoyed all the other books I have read by her. I just can't help but thinking "Did Bloom really write this book? It just doesn't match the others I have read. And... How much of this gossip is true?'Still giving it...4 stars...more

How she passed the physical and maintained her secret identity is the stuff of this book.I listened to the audio as I read this book. The narrator is Bahni Turpin, who has narrated quite a few books. I recently read and listened to three of the four Freedman/Johnson series written by Laila Ibrahim. Bahni narrated all of these. The first in the series is Yellow Crocus.I want to share with you the blurb from Audible about this book which describes the story succinctly:"From Sarah Bird comes the compelling, hidden story of Cathy Williams, a former slave and the first woman to ever serve in the US Army “Here's the first thing you need to know about Miss Cathy Williams: I am the daughter of a daughter of a queen and my Mama never let me forget it." Missouri, 1864 - Powerful, epic, and compelling, Daughter of a Daughter of a Queen shines light on a nearly forgotten figure in history. Cathy Williams was born and lived a slave - until the Union army comes and destroys the only world she’s known. Separated from her family, she makes the impossible decision - to fight in the army disguised as a man with the Buffalo Soldiers. With courage and wit, Cathy must not only fight for her survival and freedom in the ultimate man’s world, but never give up on her mission to find her family, and the man she loves. Beautiful, strong, and impactful, Cathy’s story is one that illustrates the force of hidden history come to light, the strength of women, and the power of love."4 starsATY Prompt: 2. review: Historical Fiction at its best: when I read about a historical event I had no idea occurred. And LEARN!!The event covered in this book is the explosioHistorical Fiction at its best: when I read about a historical event I had no idea occurred. And LEARN!!The event covered in this book is the explosion of the SB Pulaski on June 14, 1838. It was taking 37 crew and 150-160 passengers from Savannah to Baltimore Maryland. 58 of that number survived. Only four life boats, two of which were so dried out from the sun that they were useless. The other two carried 21 of the survivors to shore. The rest of the survivors clung to large pieces of the wreckage until they were rescued, some being in the water up to four days. Callahan expertly weaves this story with a present day narrative: Everly Winthrop is asked to curate an exhibit of recovered articles from the disaster.I purchased the audible to listen along while reading and it was an excellent addition. My only problem was keeping track of the myriad passengers on board and their relations to each other.Highly recommend.4.5 stars...more

Belize is a society moving from colonialism to independence.From Wikipedia:Beka Lamb is the debut novel from Belizean writer Zee Edgell, published in 1982 as part of the Heinemann Caribbean Writers Series. It won the Fawcett Society Book Prize in 1982 and was one of the first novels from Belize to gain international recognition. In 2022, it was included on the "Big Jubilee Read" list of 70 books by Commonwealth authors, selected to celebrate the Platinum Jubilee of Elizabeth II.My impressions:This is the story of Beka's maturation in the politically unstable Belize of the 1950's. My first indication that I would like the book was the inclusion of the name MY name was derived from. Beka won an essay contest at St Cecilia's Academy. Beka thought she could never win. She cannot really celebrate, though. Her best friend Toycie Qualo has died and the traditional Belizean nine-day wake has yet to occur.From this point, the story is a 7 month flashback leading up to ultimately winning this essay contest and her friend’s death. Only by thinking back on everything can Beka move on.Well written and well thought of, the book is an excellent way to understand Belizean culture and politics. The story ends on a positive note, so I felt my time reading it well spent.5 stars...more

review: Terrorists have given an airline pilot a choice: crash his plane with 140 "souls" on board and save the lives of his kidnapped family, or land the plaTerrorists have given an airline pilot a choice: crash his plane with 140 "souls" on board and save the lives of his kidnapped family, or land the plane, saving passengers and crew but resulting in his family's deaths. His answer is that neither the people on the plane nor his family are going to die.Author T.J. Newman worked as a flight attendant for Virgin America and Alaska Airlines between 2011 and 2021. Her years of experience with airplanes and the people on them — crew and passengers alike — give Falling authenticity. (Almost incredibly, she says she wrote much of the manuscript on redeyes while passengers slept.)A planeload of characters would be far too many to follow, of course. Fortunately, Newman tracks a relatively small group: the pilot and his family, the flight’s crew, a handful of passengers, the bad guys, and some key people on the ground. Brief flashbacks illustrate how characters became who they are, making them three-dimensional and sympathetic (and ultimately suggesting the book’s surprising conclusion). We see Bill in flight school, then as a husband and father. We meet the bad guys bonding as children watching an American movie in a faraway country. More than once, crew members cleverly resort to technological Jujitsu and turn weaknesses into strengths. A very old-school skill of Bill’s proves to be valuable precisely because it’s one that most people aren’t familiar with any longer.You might stop breathing during the harrowing final approach, but first-time author Newman lands the story thoughtfully and confidently.Most of this  comes from the following source:https://www.washingtonindependentrevi...Written by Randy Cepuch, he is a retired business writer and million-mile flier who, since writing this , has flown to and from LAX — uneventfully.5 stars...more

review: Most of you are probably familiar with Whitehead's Pulitzer Prize winning books: The Underground Railroad and The Underground Railroad. This is differMost of you are probably familiar with Whitehead's Pulitzer Prize winning books: The Underground Railroad and The Underground Railroad. This is different in scope from those, but it too has a message. Set in Harlem during the late-1950s and early-1960s, the novel portrays African American life in New York City during a time of social upheaval. It is a crime novel, but has historical fiction elements as well.Our protaganist is Ray Carney. He is the son of a now-dead Harlem criminal. Ray wants respectability for his family. He owns a furniture store. As the book progresses, though, Ray becomes more involved in crime. From selling the occasional stolen TV, he becomes involved with former associates of his father, very dangerous people. His cousin Freddy is even more involved than Ray and Ray treads on dangerous ground because of trying to protect Freddy.The story is told in three parts and each part has its own antagonist. The scale of the antagonists escalates from street hoodlum and thief to influential community leader to one of the richest men in the city. At each step, the threat of violence posed by the antagonist increases in accordance with the adversary’s material resources. The more money a person possesses, the less they need to worry about legal ramifications.There are many messages in this story, but, to me, the prevalent theme is that of racism in mid-century America. Racism is so prevalent that even ambitious characters like Ray cannot see an end to it.This is my fourth book read that is written by Colson Whitehead. Harlem Shuffle does not fit the mode of story telling that I have associated with the author in the first three. This book is more crime than historical fiction. However I can tell that the message of this book is one near and dear to the author. It contains the author's skill in providing the prettily turned phrase and presents a well written narrative.4 stars...more

review: Written in a foreward, 2 short stories, another foreward, and 3 short stories taken from a journal.The first short story isBela (really more a novellaWritten in a foreward, 2 short stories, another foreward, and 3 short stories taken from a journal.The first short story isBela (really more a novella)An unnamed narrator meets a man on a train who proceeds to tell him a story. Maxim Maximych (the man) describes the main character of his story Pechorin, as a man full of contradictions: "he'd spend the whole day out hunting in rain or cold" and "think nothing of it," yet "he'd sit in his room and at the least puff of wind reckon he'd caught a chill". While attending a wedding, Pechorin is attracted to the younger sister of the bride, Bela. This story is about the relationship between Pechorin and Bela that ensues.The second short story Maxim MaximychMaxim Maximych and the narrator are reunited. The two encounter a rude servant who just happens to be the servant of Pechorin. Maximych wishes to re-unite with Pechorin, does, and is sadly disappointed. Pechorin wants nothing to do with him.Foreward to Last Three StoriesPechorin is now dead and the narrator states that the next three stories are based on his journals. Pechorin has many valuable things to say which should be shared.Book III The First Extract From Pechorin's DiaryTamanTaman is a town in which Pechorin is staying. There he meets smugglers: a blind boy, a young woman and an old woman. Pechorin is a master manipulator, yet the blind boy and the young woman outsmart him. Contrast that with the story Bela, where Pechorin uses Bela.Book IV The Second Extract From Pechorin's DiaryThe FatalistBook V The Third Extract from Pechorin's DiaryPrincess MaryShe is beautiful and naïve. She has a lot of admirers, but they bore her. She initially finds Grushnitsky interesting, but he eventually bores her as well. She tries to decipher Pechorin, but fails. He, on the other hand, knows her thoughts too well; he uses this advantage to manipulate her and create chaos not only in her life, but in the lives of many other characters.The Byronic HeroPechorin is considered to have the characteristics of the Byronic Hero: astute, alluring, self-destructive, selfish, and very critical of his society. Contrast that with the Perfect Hero who is a paragon of virtue, embodies everything good about humanity, is strong (mentally and physically), uncompromising, selfless, kind, and decisive.I not only read the book but learned much about it using https://www.gradesaver.com/a-hero-of-...Enjoyed the read and getting into the mind of the author.4 stars...more

review: In his novel, Gorky portrays the life of a woman who works in a Russian factory doing hard manual labour and combating poverty and hunger, among otherIn his novel, Gorky portrays the life of a woman who works in a Russian factory doing hard manual labour and combating poverty and hunger, among other hardships. Pelageya Nilovna Vlasova is the real protagonist; her husband, a heavy drunkard, physically assaults her and leaves all the responsibility for raising their son, Pavel Vlasov, to her, but unexpectedly dies. Pavel noticeably begins to emulate his father in his drunkenness and stammer, but suddenly becomes involved in revolutionary activities. Abandoning drinking, Pavel starts to bring books to his home. Being illiterate and having no political interest, Nilovna is at first cautious about Pavel's new activities. However, she wants to help him. Pavel is shown as the main revolutionary character. Nevertheless Nilovna, moved by her maternal feelings and, though uneducated, overcoming her political ignorance to become involved in revolution, is considered the true protagonist of the novel.Mother is the only big novel of Gorky on the Russian revolutionary movement; however, of all his novels, it is possibly the least successful. Nevertheless, it remains the best known work of Gorky among the author's other novels. Modern critics consider it Gorky's most important pre-revolutionary novel because of the vivid image of his "God-Builder" ideas.I did appreciate 'Mother's' character growth as I progressed through the novel. But the book was repetitive and frequently boring.3 stars...more

It is 5 short stories and a novella and the time period is NOW. NOW with all the racial problems we are beginning to recognize as endemic in the US. Let me emphasize that I am painfully aware of the cultural problems in the US. However, I cannot rate this book and its stories highly. I just did not appreciate the writing style which in the first two stories were written in a kind of letter format. Especially in the second story, it seemed like scolding.There are 5 short stories in this book take up 28% of the content.SS1: Control Negro (15 pages) A Father uses his illegitimate son in a racial experiment. 3 stars because it is thought provokingSS2: Virginia Is Not Your Home (11 pages) Someone seems to be chiding a woman as she grows through childhood to old age. Not really sure what the message is. 1 starSS4: Buying a House Ahead of the Apocolypse (6 pages) Just a bunch of bullet points. 1 starSS5: The King of Xandria (16 pages) A proud man from Nigeria cannot understand why the Virginia teachers think his son less than perfect. 4 starsNovella: My Monticello (179 pages) Their neighborhood is on fire. They take refuge in Monticello, the historical home of Da' Naisha's ancestors, Thomas Jefferson and Sally Hemmings. 3.5 StarsHaving given you my opinion, I DO want you to know that the likes of Roxanne Gay, Colson Whitehead and Charles Yu have praised this book to the skies. So don't listen to me; see for yourself.3 stars...more

review: I thought this book very well-written and an eye opener. The author, Mark Sundeen, has divided his book into three stories.Ethan and Sarah - find theiI thought this book very well-written and an eye opener. The author, Mark Sundeen, has divided his book into three stories.Ethan and Sarah - find their dream farm in Northeast Missouri. Their goal: live without electricity or petroleum. They own no car, refrigerator, water heater, furnace, washing machine, computer or cell phone. The think of it as the simple life, but it is FAR from simple. Plus it is isolated. l admire these people, but I could not do it.Greg and Olivia - live in Detroit and practice urban farming on their one acre. Their story is inspiring. But the story of Detroit and its demise is depressing. The author and his wife, Cedar, live in Montana. Mark described the lives of these couples to Cedar. She said:“You don’t really want to live like that.” “I don’t?” “I know people who want to live like that, and you’re not one of them. You’re attracted to the ideas, but living back-to-the-land is not an intellectual decision. People do it because they love it.”Mark reflects:"I was not the type to fill my boots with snow just to get a closer look at an owl. I was the type to read a book about such a person.”Me too, Mark. Me too!!5 starsBTW, I found this book because I wanted to learn more about the agrarian, Wendell Berry. I'll have to read Berry to find out more. This book mentions him, but I experienced so much more....more

review: Niall Williams and Christine Breen have gone to great lengths to describe their lives in Ireland. They are originally from the US and have been Irish Niall Williams and Christine Breen have gone to great lengths to describe their lives in Ireland. They are originally from the US and have been Irish residents for 37 years. Both are in their 60's and their loving marriage is highlighted as well as the obvious respect they have for each other.The impetus for this sharing is the coming of wind turbines to the area. The landscape is going to change dramatically. At the very least, many of the old stone walls will be removed. Niall and Chris are both worried about the negative effects these will have on their lives.We read much about the beautiful plants in their garden: trees, flowers and produce. Niall also shares some musings on memory, the lessons learned from gardening, and remoteness.As a Catholic, I was especially touched by the outdoor mass celebrated by Father Tim. Niall was touched as well.I was introduced to Wendell Berry, who writes "superbly and urgently about nature".The descriptive writing of Williams is a treasure. I can picture myself being with the couple in the west of Ireland.I see more Niall Williams (AND Wendell Berry) in my reading future.5 stars...more

review: A beautifully insightful book. So many topics explored: marriage, love, happiness, sorrow, grief, betrayal.Graham and Annie are a couple living in CamA beautifully insightful book. So many topics explored: marriage, love, happiness, sorrow, grief, betrayal.Graham and Annie are a couple living in Cambridge, Mass., who've been happily married nearly 30 years; the husband suddenly dies and the wife discovers he had been having an affair. Her known world is, thus, doubly shattered. Other relationships are shared: Graham and his first wife, Frieda; his son, Lucas and wife Jeanne; their daughter Sarah and her relationship with Tom; Edith and her gay ex-husband.Other realtionships grow from these: the friendship of Annie and Frieda; Lucas seeing Annie as mother; Sarah seeing Frieda as mother.I marveled at all the ways the characters did interact and learned much from these interactions.Very well written and a compelling page turner.Book Club Discussion 6/28Seven people attended and three of them hated the book, one was non-committal and three loved it. So be fore-warned: this book is not for everybody. Bottom line: I could identify with these characters; others could not.5 stars...more
